	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Valsuvious</b><br /><i>How do you really know if you are trying to maximize your damage output in a shaman role?  When you are one of the first ones to always get summoned when the tank goes down.  I tend to be #2 alot, after our best mage.  Just tonight I got summoned three times in Glorification when the mobs were at 0 - 5%, and most of them were just from one bane cast, and alot of crit nuking <img src="images/smilies/frown.gif" border="0" alt="" title="frown" smilieid="2" /></i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Damage output and aggro (cause of summoning) do not necessarily go hand-in-hand. A Wizard can do up to 6x our best nuke (with a crit, which is more likely because Wizards tend to max those AA faster than Shamans) yet that will not even generate the same aggro as 3 tics of Blood of Saryrn. <br />
<br />
One of our biggest complaints is the fact that we stack so poorly on raids because: <br />
1.- our nukes blow frogs, and <br />
2.- our DOTs generate far too much aggro in relation to the damage they do, and of course . . .<br />
3.- our heals look like Bind Wound on a tank taking quad 1200's<br />
<br />
The combination of these things makes us seriously unstackable. Poor DPS combined with poor healing. If we could consistantly stack 2 DOTs and nuke for 1.2-2.4K with a fast nuke (half the cast time of VS) or heal for a decent amount (1800 + focus and AA modifiers) while the DOTs were ticcing, we would actually contribute in a farily signicficat fashion.</p>
	
	
	
